msgid "# Backups and restorations"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:4
msgid ""
"In this chapter you will learn how to backup and restore your data with "
"Linux."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:12
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
":heavy_check_mark: use the `tar` and `cpio` command to make a backup;   \n"
":heavy_check_mark: check their backups and restore data;   \n"
":heavy_check_mark: compress or decompress their backups.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:14
msgid ":checkered_flag: **backup**, **restore**, **compression**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:17
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Knowledge**: :star: :star: :star:   \n"
"**Complexity**: :star: :star:    \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:24
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Note\n"
"    Throughout this chapter the command structures use \"device\" to specify both a target location for backup, and the source location when restoring. The device can be either external media or a local file. You should get a feel for this as the chapter unfolds, but you can always refer back to this note for clarification if you need to.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:26
msgid ""
"The backup will answer a need to conserve and restore data in a sure and "
"effective way."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:28
msgid "The backup allows you to protect yourself from the following:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:32
msgid ""
"**Destruction**: voluntary or involuntary. Human or technical. Virus, ..."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:32
msgid "**Deletion**: voluntary or involuntary. Human or technical. Virus, ..."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:32
msgid "**Integrity** : data becomes unusable."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:34
msgid ""
"No system is infallible, no human is infallible, so to avoid losing data, it "
"must be backed up to be able to restore after a problem."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:36
msgid ""
"The backup media should be kept in another room (or building) than the "
"server so that a disaster does not destroy the server and the backups."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:38
msgid ""
"In addition, the administrator must regularly check that the media are still "
"readable."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:42
msgid "There are two principles, the **backup** and the **archive**."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:45
msgid "The archive destroys the information source after the operation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:45
msgid "The backup preserves the source of information after the operation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/09-backups.md:47
msgid ""
"These operations consist of saving information in a file, on a peripheral or "
"a supported media (tapes, disks, ...)."
msgstr ""

